<CaseStudy slug="sop-mcp">
  <p class="lead reveal">A team's knowledge usually lives in a folder of markdown SOPs and FAQs that nobody reads at the moment they need it. sop-mcp turns that folder into something an AI client can answer from, with a citation back to the exact document. It is the plumbing that lets a non-technical team turn its own handbook into an assistant, and it installs in about two minutes.</p>

  <h2 class="reveal">The problem: the handbook nobody opens in time</h2>
  <p class="reveal">Generic "markdown knowledge base" servers exist, but they are built for developers and assume a technical setup. The person who actually owns the SOPs, an ops or HR lead, cannot stand one up without asking engineering. The goal was a server sized for that specific job, that a non-technical admin can turn on themselves, and that cites its sources so the answers are checkable.</p>

  <h2 class="reveal">The approach: three tools, a handbook, a two-minute install</h2>
  <p class="reveal">It is a Model Context Protocol server exposing three read-only tools: <code>search_handbook</code> (keyword and heading matching, returning cited excerpts), <code>get_document</code>, and <code>list_documents</code>. Each document is also an MCP resource. It ships with a full sample handbook so the first run works before anyone edits a thing, and the README opens with the two-minute path: an npx one-liner and the exact config to paste.</p>

  <pre class="reveal"><code>&gt; search_handbook  "refund window"
  refund-policy.md#eligibility   "...full refund within 30 days if..."
  refund-policy.md#exceptions    "...opened software is non-refundable..."</code></pre>

  <h2 class="reveal">Correcting a stale guide by reading the types</h2>
  <p class="reveal">I scaffolded it with a builder skill, but the skill's examples were written against an old SDK: an outdated version and a deprecated way of registering tools. Rather than trust the generated shape, I read the installed SDK's own type definitions to confirm the current contract, that tool inputs take a raw schema and that a successful result carries structured content while an error is exempt. That check avoided two classes of runtime error the stale guide would have baked in. Reading the source of truth beats trusting the tutorial.</p>

  <h2 class="reveal">Security by construction, not by string-filtering</h2>
  <p class="reveal">A tool that reads files by name is exactly where path traversal creeps in. Instead of trying to filter dangerous inputs, I removed the possibility: the server loads every document into memory once at startup, and <code>get_document</code> is a lookup against that in-memory set. A caller's input never reaches the filesystem at all, so there is nothing to traverse. I confirmed it with nine attack strings (parent-directory hops, absolute paths, separators, a null byte); every one returns a friendly "no such document" listing the real ids, never a file.</p>

  <h2 class="reveal">How I verified it</h2>
  <ul class="reveal">
    <li><strong>Tests:</strong> <strong>24 of 24</strong> passing (handbook parsing, search ranking, document lookup, the traversal attacks, truncation).</li>
    <li><strong>Live session:</strong> a scripted client drove the built server over real stdio, exactly as Claude Desktop would, and asserted <strong>11 of 11</strong> steps: tool discovery, search with citations, document fetch, the traversal defense, and resource reads.</li>
    <li><strong>Ship-ready:</strong> a packaging dry-run confirms the published bundle carries the server plus the sample handbook, so a zero-config install works on the first try. A fresh-context review passed with no material findings.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="reveal">Why I point to this one</h2>
  <p class="reveal">This is what "AI plumbing" looks like when it is built for adoption: a small, honest tool a non-technical team can turn on themselves, that cites its sources and cannot damage what it reads. Enablement is not just the flashy demo; it is the boring, trustworthy pipe that makes the demo real on Monday.</p>
</CaseStudy>
